reasoning:
I’m going to start with the circle of competence, because that’s Step One in my playbook. Advertising technology, search algorithms and all the machine‐learning wizardry that underlies Alphabet’s business is far outside the bakery, soft drink and simple franchise businesses I’ve spent a lifetime understanding. When I can’t explain a business in plain English, I don’t own it. 

On the moat front, Google clearly has scale advantages and entrenched market share in search and digital advertising. Those traits might qualify as a moat for a tech investor, but I’m not comfortable measuring it against a consumer staples moat like Coke’s brand power or See’s Candies’ local pricing flexibility. 

I’ve got zero insight into management here – the existing data says "insufficient" – and I need to believe management acts like owners before I bet alongside them. 

With no financials or consistency history in the report, I can’t assess the balance sheet or earnings durability. A fortress balance sheet matters to me, and absent any figures, I’m left guessing. 

Valuation? No intrinsic‐value estimate. No margin of safety. Price without value is speculation, and Berkshire doesn’t dabble in speculation. 

Long‐term prospects for online advertising might be strong, but rapid technological change and regulatory risk keep me uneasy. 

Compared to what I own – Apple for its consumer ecosystem, Coca-Cola for decades of consistent returns, BNSF for simple infrastructure – Alphabet doesn’t fit. When I don’t understand, I say “no.” In this case, I’ll simply stay on the sidelines with a neutral signal until I or my team can truly wrap our heads around the business and its financials.
